{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491123","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491123"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:33:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:33:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"838"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"838","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/838"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.42,0.17,0.05,0.13,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"838"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92399"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"838","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/838"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"838"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75714"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"549"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31582"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31583"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40791"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92399"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-woman presents with a two-month history of a painless midline swelling in her neck (Image). The swelling moves up when she protrudes her tongue. An ultrasound shows a 3 cm cystic swelling above and separate from a normal thyroid. The patient is not particularly keen on any treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the expected natural history of this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No change","Spontaneous resolution","Malignant transformation","Laryngeal compression","Infection and fistula formation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe history and ultrasound findings above are typical of a thyroglossal cyst. Though these are thought of as a childhood condition, one third of thyroglossal cysts do not become apparent and are not detected until after the age of 20 years. The standard recommendation is resection (Sistrunk procedure) for cosmetic reasons and the risk of infection. Up to one half of thyroglossal cysts may become infected, and any infection can be treated with antibiotic therapy. Fistula formation is rare and these cysts do not normally resolve spontaneously. The risk of malignancy in a thyroglossal cyst is less than 1%, and the majority of associated malignancies are papillary thyroid carcinomas. Large thyroglossal cysts can lead to laryngeal remodelling, however this is relatively uncommon. Since thyroglossal cysts are not invasive, excision of the cyst generally resolves any compression of the larynx.\u00a0If the patient declines treatment or is not a surgical candidate then the natural history is relatively benign and \u003Cstrong\u003Eno change\u003C/strong\u003E will be expected.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most thyroglossal cysts present in childhood and are of little consequence to the patient."],"references":["Chou J, Walters A, Hage R, et al. Thyroglossal duct cysts: anatomy, embryology and treatment. Surg Radiol Anat 2013; 35:875."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75714"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"838"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14439"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14439","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14439"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b98086a9-dc29-43e9-82d3-8487537e3c64.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://